<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1367,1862]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1367,1393]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks</emphasis>
. All essential characteristics of the present Japanese material agree well with the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G." box="[159,441,1403,1430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref19272" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G. (1966) Studies on the North American aquatic Oligochaeta. III. Lumbriculidae and additional notes and records of other families. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 118, 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1966">Brinkhurst &amp; Cook 1966</bibRefCitation>
), the only account prior to this paper (subsequent accounts summarize data of the original description). Spermathecae were &quot;not observed&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G." box="[701,1023,1439,1465]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref19272" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G. (1966) Studies on the North American aquatic Oligochaeta. III. Lumbriculidae and additional notes and records of other families. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 118, 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1966">Brinkhurst &amp; Cook 1966: 19</bibRefCitation>
) in the original material, whereas the single sexually mature Japanese specimen available to us had one pair of spermathecae. The spermathecal ampullae of the present material were small, but they contained sperm masses (
<figureCitation box="[923,1009,1511,1537]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1225,1249]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,425,1197]" captionTargetId="figure-154@5.[151,1436,417,1202]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Aulodrilus americanus Brinkhurst &amp; Cook from Sapporo, Japan. A, dorsal chaeta in III; B and C variation of distal ends of dorsal chaetae in anterior segments; D, dorsal chaeta in a mid-segment; E, the same in a posterior segment; F, sagittal section of anterior segments; G, parasagittal section of genital segments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671500/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
) and hence can be considered as completely formed. Occasional absence of spermathecae has been observed in other tubificines, for example, in 
<taxonomicName authority="tubifex" class="Clitellata" family="Tubificidae" genus="Tubifex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tubifex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Tubifex tubifex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Brinkhurst 1971)" baseAuthorityName="Brinkhurst" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[242,684,1583,1609]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Ilyodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="templetoni">
<emphasis box="[242,476,1583,1609]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Ilyodrilus templetoni</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O." box="[490,676,1583,1609]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="444 - 625" refId="ref19049" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. (1971) Part 2. Systematics, 8. Family Tubificidae. In: Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Jamieson, B. G. M. (Eds.), &quot; Aquatic Oligochaeta of the World &quot;. Oliver and Boyd, Edinburgh, pp. 444 - 625." type="book chapter" year="1971">Brinkhurst 1971</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Brinkhurst 1978)" baseAuthorityName="Brinkhurst" baseAuthorityYear="1978" box="[768,1195,1583,1609]" class="Clitellata" family="Tubificidae" genus="Teneridrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mastix">
<emphasis box="[768,984,1583,1609]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Teneridrilus mastix</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O." box="[999,1187,1583,1609]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="2166 - 2175" refId="ref19110" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. (1978) Freshwater Oligochaeta in Canada. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 56, 2166 - 2175. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / z 78 - 292" type="journal article" year="1978">Brinkhurst 1978</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and absence of spermathecae may be an intraspecific variation also in this species. Furthermore, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G." box="[1022,1321,1619,1646]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref19272" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G. (1966) Studies on the North American aquatic Oligochaeta. III. Lumbriculidae and additional notes and records of other families. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 118, 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1966">Brinkhurst &amp; Cook (1966)</bibRefCitation>
described eversible pseudopenes in the original description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[737,993,1655,1681]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[737,993,1655,1681]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Aulodrilus americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, the present new material has true penes as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Baker, H. R. &amp; Brinkhurst, R. O." box="[430,756,1691,1717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="936 - 965" refId="ref18767" refString="Baker, H. R. &amp; Brinkhurst, R. O. (1981) A revision of the genus Monopylephorus and redefinition of the subfamilies Rhyacodrilinae and Branchiurinae (Tubifcidae: Oligochaeta). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 59, 936 - 965. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / z 81 - 134" type="journal article" year="1981">Baker and Brinkhurst (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, because they are two-layered, solid structures, composed of the wall of the penial sac and end of the atrial wall, and have cuticular coverings
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1367,1862]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The segmental position of the genital organs in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[752,917,1764,1790]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[752,917,1764,1790]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not originally described, but the present specimen has genital organs located int the normal position of 
<taxonomicName box="[842,970,1799,1825]" class="Clitellata" family="Naididae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplotaxida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tubificinae">Tubificinae</taxonomicName>
(male pores and spermathecal pores in XI and X, respectively). Unlike many other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bretscher" authorityYear="1899" box="[608,726,1835,1861]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[608,726,1835,1861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Aulodrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, extra testes were not found in the present specimen.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671504" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4671504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671504/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" startId="6.[151,250,788,812]" targetBox="[151,1436,166,765]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,788,849]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,788,812]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">FIGURE 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook" authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[281,715,789,813]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[281,511,789,813]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aulodrilus americanus</emphasis>
Brinkhurst &amp; Cook
</taxonomicName>
, from Sapporo, Japan.SEM photomicrographs of dorsal chaetal bundle (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,178,824,848]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A</emphasis>
) and two chaetae (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[371,388,825,849]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">B</emphasis>
) in a mid- segment.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,895,1353]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<bibRefCitation author="Liang, Y. L. &amp; Wang, H. Z. &amp; Xie, Z. C." box="[199,408,895,921]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="54 - 61" refId="ref20318" refString="Liang, Y. L., Wang, H. Z. &amp; Xie, Z. C. (1998) Studies on the aquatic Oligochaeta of China. IV. Diagnoses of new records and rare species of Naididae and Tubificidae. Acta Hydrobiologica Sinica, 22, 54 - 61. [in Chinese with English abstract]" type="journal article" year="1998">
Liang 
<emphasis box="[271,327,895,921]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
(1998)
</bibRefCitation>
showed no split of distal ends of chaetae and depicted a membrane between short upper and long lower teeth of chaetae from X on in their 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[679,936,931,957]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[679,936,931,957]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aulodrilus americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1005,1076,931,957]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">China</collectingCountry>
. The brush-like form of chaetae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[181,344,967,993]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[181,344,967,993]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized in observation without high magnifications, and such chaetae appear from VI or VII. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[234,396,1003,1029]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[234,396,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Liang, Y. L. &amp; Wang, H. Z. &amp; Xie, Z. C." box="[539,749,1003,1029]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="54 - 61" refId="ref20318" refString="Liang, Y. L., Wang, H. Z. &amp; Xie, Z. C. (1998) Studies on the aquatic Oligochaeta of China. IV. Diagnoses of new records and rare species of Naididae and Tubificidae. Acta Hydrobiologica Sinica, 22, 54 - 61. [in Chinese with English abstract]" type="journal article" year="1998">
Liang 
<emphasis box="[611,668,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
(1998)
</bibRefCitation>
might not be 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[905,1068,1003,1029]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[905,1068,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The taxonomic position of their 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[151,313,1039,1065]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[151,313,1039,1065]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered provisional until the segmental location and accurate structure of the different 
<typeStatus box="[151,210,1075,1101]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">types</typeStatus>
of chaetae has been reinvestigated in the reference material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,895,1353]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1110,1136]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Distribution</emphasis>
. This species has been recorded in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G." box="[941,1231,1111,1137]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref19272" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G. (1966) Studies on the North American aquatic Oligochaeta. III. Lumbriculidae and additional notes and records of other families. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 118, 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1966">Brinkhurst &amp; Cook 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O." box="[1244,1432,1111,1137]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="137 - 143" refId="ref19006" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. (1967) The distribution of aquatic oligochaetes in Saginaw Bay, Lake Huron. Limnology and Oceanography, 12, 137 - 143. https: // doi. org / 10.4319 / lo. 1967.12.1.0137" type="journal article" year="1967">Brinkhurst 1967</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brinkhurst, R. O." box="[151,210,1147,1173]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="2166 - 2175" refId="ref19110" refString="Brinkhurst, R. O. (1978) Freshwater Oligochaeta in Canada. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 56, 2166 - 2175. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / z 78 - 292" type="journal article" year="1978">1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiltunen, J. K." box="[222,387,1147,1173]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="433 - 454" refId="ref19962" refString="Hiltunen, J. K. (1967) Some oligochaetes from Lake Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 86, 433 - 454. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3224267" type="journal article" year="1967">Hiltunen 1967</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiltunen, J. K." box="[398,457,1147,1173]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="260 - 264" refId="ref20000" refString="Hiltunen, J. K. (1969) Distribution of oligochaetes in western Lake Erie, 1961. Limnology and Oceanography, 14, 260 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.4319 / lo. 1969.14.2.0260" type="journal article" year="1969">1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Stimpson, K. S. &amp; Brice, J. R. &amp; Barbour, M. S. &amp; Nalco, P. H." box="[470,706,1147,1174]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="384 - 394" refId="ref21665" refString="Stimpson, K. S., Brice, J. R., Barbour, M. S. &amp; Nalco, P. H. (1975) Distribution and abundance of inshore oligochaetes in Lake Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 94, 384 - 394. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3225503" type="journal article" year="1975">
Stimpson 
<emphasis box="[583,640,1147,1173]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
1975
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, D. R." box="[718,873,1147,1173]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="115 - 164" refId="ref21511" refString="Spencer, D. R. (1980) The aquatic Oligochaeta of the St. Lawrence Great Lakes region. In: Brinkhurst, R. O. &amp; Cook, D. G. (Eds.), Aquatic Oligochaete Biology. Plenum, New York, p. 115 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4613 - 3048 - 6 _ 8" type="book chapter" year="1980">Spencer 1980</bibRefCitation>
) and in 
<collectingCountry box="[966,1030,1147,1173]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Ohtaka, unpublished data in 
<bibRefCitation author="Timm, T." pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="67 - 81" refId="ref21813" refString="Timm, T. (1999 a). Distribution of freshwater oligochaetes in the west and east coastal regions of the North Pacific Ocean. Hydrobiologia, 406, 67 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1003749519662" type="journal article" year="1999">Timm 1999a</bibRefCitation>
), showing circum-Pacific distribution (
<bibRefCitation author="Timm, T." box="[665,816,1183,1209]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="67 - 81" refId="ref21813" refString="Timm, T. (1999 a). Distribution of freshwater oligochaetes in the west and east coastal regions of the North Pacific Ocean. Hydrobiologia, 406, 67 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1003749519662" type="journal article" year="1999">Timm 1999a</bibRefCitation>
). These records are formally the first of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,218,1219,1245]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Japan</collectingCountry>
. The Japanese habitats were cool waters, including spring-fed streams in Sapporo (water temperature 10.5°C), Ushiwatari stream in Yuza Town (12.3 °C), and a brook in a sphagnum bog of Ozegahara Mire, 
<collectingRegion box="[1225,1433,1255,1281]" country="Japan" name="Gunma" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Gunma Prefecture</collectingRegion>
. Differing from many other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bretscher" authorityYear="1899" box="[453,571,1291,1317]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[453,571,1291,1317]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Aulodrilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species living in warm waters, the preference of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brinkhurst &amp; Cook. Comparison" authorityYear="1966" box="[1111,1272,1291,1317]" class="Clitellata" family="Randiellidae" genus="Aulodrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enchytraeida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis box="[1111,1272,1291,1317]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for cool-water habitats is apparently unique.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
